Consumer Insight Analysis

Omorede Iguma

05-09-2025

1 Synopsis

This project explores the E-commerce Customer Behaviour Dataset provided on Kaggle by Laksika Tharmalingam. This dataset provides a comprehensive view of customer behaviour within an e-commerce platform. Each entry in the dataset corresponds to a unique customer, offering a detailed breakdown of their interactions and transactions. The information is crafted to facilitate a nuanced analysis of customer preferences, engagement patterns, and satisfaction levels, aiding businesses in making data-driven decisions to enhance the customer experience.

Note: This dataset was synthetically generated for illustrative purposes, and any resemblance to real individuals or scenarios is coincidental.

2.3 Handling Missing Values

The Satisfaction_Level column was re-coded in order to use the most occurring value to populate the two missing cases in the column. This was done using the mode function from the “DescTools” library package.

df <- df %>%
            mutate(Satisfaction_Level_Coded = case_when(
            satisfaction_level == "Unsatisfied" ~ "0",
            satisfaction_level == "Neutral" ~ "1",
            satisfaction_level == "Satisfied" ~ "2"
            ))
library(DescTools)

2.4 Creating an Age Category Variable

An age category column was created so a descriptive statistics can be conducted and later assigned as a factor for a subsequent one-way analysis of variance test in order to determine if there is a significant difference for total amount spend by different age groups.

df <- df %>%
            mutate(age_category = case_when(
            age >= 20 & age <= 29 ~ "20-29",
            age >= 30 & age <= 39 ~ "30-39",
            age >= 40 & age <= 49 ~ "40-49"
            ))

2.6 Inverse Normal Distribution Transformation

Due to an independent samples t-test requiring the dependent variable to be approximately normally distributed for each group, an inverse normal distribution was done to achieve a roughly normal distribution.

2.6.1 Rank the Data

Firstly, the Total_Spend variable was ranked, with the average computed when there is a tie and any missing values be kept.

total_spend_ranking <- rank(df$total_spend, 
                            na.last = "keep", 
                            ties.method = "average")

2.6.2 Fractional Ranking and the Inverse Normal Distribution

The ranked data was subtracted from 0.5 and divided by the sum of the ranked data. This was to ensure the values ranged from 0 to 1. The “not” operator (!), in conjunction with the is.na function, was used to keep non-missing values. The mean and standard deviation of the Total_Spend variable were computed, which would be used for the inverse normal distribution. The fractional ranking, mean, and standard deviation of the Total_Spend variable were fed into the qnorm function, which generated the inverse normal distribution of the Total_Spend variable. The values were then saved to a new variable named Total_Spend_Transformed.

fractional_rank <- (total_spend_ranking - 0.5) / sum(!is.na(total_spend_ranking))

total_spend_mean <- mean(df$total_spend)

total_spend_std_dev <- sd(df$total_spend)

IDF <- qnorm(fractional_rank, 
             total_spend_mean, 
             total_spend_std_dev)

df["total_spend_transformed"] <- qnorm(fractional_rank, 
                                       total_spend_mean, 
                                       total_spend_std_dev)

2.6.3 Total Spend now Approximately Normally Distributed (Histogram & QQ-Plot)

hist(df$total_spend_transformed, xlab = "Total Spend", 
     main = "Histogram of Total_Spend_Transformed")

ggqqplot(df$total_spend_transformed)

4 Customer Segmentation

A k-means cluster analysis was performed on the variables Age, Total_Spend, and Items_Purchased. First, the three variables were selected and assigned to a new data frame called k_means_df. Next, within the “factoextra” library package, the function “fviz_nbclust” was used to determine the optimal number of clusters for the k-means analysis. The elbow method was employed. The graph indicated an elbow around cluster number 3, suggesting that three clusters are optimal for the k-means. The built-in “kmeans” function was then used to perform the cluster analysis, requesting 3 clusters, with a maximum of 50 iterations and an nstart value of 25.

Note: An nstart value of 25 was chosen because the algorithm attempts multiple initial centroid configurations and reports on the best one, so an nstart of 25 will generate 25 initial random centroids and choose the best one for the algorithm.

4.1 Determining the Optimal Numbers of Clusters to Use

k_means_df <- select(df, 
                     age, 
                     total_spend, 
                     items_purchased)


library(factoextra)
fviz_nbclust(x = k_means_df, 
             FUNcluster = kmeans, 
             method = "wss") +
  labs(subtitle = "Elbow Method")

4.2 Clustering Result

From the results generated, we can observe that cluster 1 comprises slightly older, moderate-spenders, cluster 2 was made up of Younger, higher-spenders, while cluster 3 consists of Older-low-spenders.

Cluster 1 (n = 117) features slightly older customers (M = 32) who purchase a moderate number of items (M = 12). Cluster 2 (n = 117) comprises younger customers (M = 30) with the highest number of items purchased (M = 18). Cluster 3 (n = 116) consists of older customers (M = 39) with the fewest items purchased (M = 9).

The total amount of money spent varied significantly across the three clusters: younger customers tend to spend more ($1311.14), slightly older customers spend a moderate amount ($748.43), while older customers tend to spend less ($473.39) and purchase fewer items. Since younger customers tend to spend more and buy more, the company should appropriately target this cluster with promotions. For older customers, marketing research should be carried out to identify ways to encourage them to spend and buy more.

K_Means_Clustering <- kmeans(k_means_df, 
                             centers = 3,
                             iter.max = 50,
                             nstart = 25)
print(K_Means_Clustering)

5 Relationship Between Gender and Membership Type

Using the sjPlot library package, the function tab_xtab was used to conduct and present the result from a chi-square test of independence between gender and membership type, while the plot_xtab function was used for the visual presentation. Other functions such as theme_minimal, xlabs and scale_fill_manual from the ggplot2 library package was used.

For the post-hoc test, the built-in function chisq.test along with $stdres was used to print only the standardised residuals. The output was then converted to a data frame, using the as.data.frame function, the standardised residuals were rounded off to one decimal, finally the column names were changed using the colnames function.

The Pearson’s Chi-squared test of independence between Gender and Membership Type suggests that the effect is statistically significant, and very large (χ² = 229.04, p < .001; Adjusted Cramer’s v = 0.81, 95% CI [0.72, 1.00]).

Note: the values in the crosstab were changed from the default black colour to white for visibility purpose due to the darkly theme used for the html output.

5.1 Post-hoc Test

Examination of standardised residuals indicated that males were highly over represented in the silver membership category (adjusted residual = 13.0) and completely absent from the bronze category (adjusted residual = -13.2). Conversely, females were significantly over represented in the bronze category (adjusted residual = 13.2) and almost absent from the silver category (adjusted residual = -13.0). No significant deviation was observed in the gold membership category (adjusted residual = 0.1 for males, -0.1 for females), indicating a roughly equal distribution of gold membership across genders.

6 Relationship Between Demographics and Spending

The descriptive statistics for the one-way anova was obtained by calculating the mean and standard deviation of the variable total spend for each age category and then rounded off to two decimals. Using the mutate function in the dplyr package, the column “Variance” was created. Furthermore, the case_when function was used to compute the individual variances for the three age categories by taking the square root of the standard deviation. The levene_test function from the rstatix library package was used to confirm whether the variances were equal. At a glace, we can observe that the variances are unequal, which was also confirmed by the Levene’s test based on median, and since the group sizes are also unequal, a Welch ANOVA was conducted. The age_category was converted to a factor variable using the as.factor built-in function.

6.1 Group Statistics

anova_descriptive <- df %>%
                          group_by(age_category) %>%
                          summarise(n = n(),
                          Mean = round(mean(total_spend), 2),
                          Standard_Deviation = round(sd(total_spend), 2))


anova_descriptive <- anova_descriptive %>%
                                          mutate(Variance = round(case_when(
                                          Standard_Deviation == 378.66 ~ sqrt(378.66),
                                          Standard_Deviation == 338.43 ~ sqrt(338.43),
                                          Standard_Deviation == 15.28 ~ sqrt(15.28)
                                          ), 2))


rmarkdown::paged_table(anova_descriptive)
df$age_category <- as.factor(df$age_category)

6.2 Levene’s Test for Equal Variances (Median)

library(rstatix)

equal_var_test <- levene_test(data = df, total_spend ~ age_category,
                              center = "median")


equal_var_test <- equal_var_test %>%
                                    mutate(statistic = round(statistic, 2),
                                          p = case_when(
                                            p <0.001 ~ "<0.001"
                                            ))

rmarkdown::paged_table(equal_var_test)

6.3 Welch ANOVA Model

A Welch ANOVA was conducted to determine whether there were significant differences in total spending based on age category. There was a statistically significant difference in total spending among the three age groups F(2,139) = 205.71, p < .001. The effect size Epsilon Squared was 0.23 (23%), indicating that the independent variable age category explained 23% of the variation in the dependent variable total spent. This was obtained using the “effectsize” library package with the function “epsilon_squared”.

Note: The function welch_anova_test from the rstatix library package, was used conduct the Welch anova. The values from the result were rounded off to two decimals, including the effect size with its confidence intervals, while the p-value was converted form a scientific notation to a more readable format. The post-hoc estimates, its confidence interval were rounded off to two decimals, while the adjusted p-value was converted from a scientific notation into a more readable format.

library(rstatix)

welch_anova <- df %>%
                      welch_anova_test(total_spend ~ age_category) %>%
                      mutate( p = case_when(
                              p <0.001 ~ "<0.001"
                              )) %>%
                      mutate(across(c(3:5), round, 2))





rmarkdown::paged_table((welch_anova))

6.4 ANOVA Effect Size

library(effectsize)

anova_effect <- epsilon_squared(aov(total_spend ~ age_category,
                                    data = df)) %>%
                                mutate(across(c(2:4), round, 2))


rmarkdown::paged_table(anova_effect)

6.5 Post-hoc Test (Games-Howell Test)

Post-hoc analysis using the Games-Howell test revealed that customers aged 20-29 spent significantly more ($1072.18 ) than those aged 30-39 ($865.07), with a mean difference of $207.12, p < .001. Similarly, those age 20-29 spent significantly more than those aged 40-49 ($499.88), with a mean difference of $572.30 Significant differences were also between the 30–39 and 40–49 age groups with a mean difference of $365.18, p < .001

post_hoc <- df %>%
                  games_howell_test(total_spend ~ age_category) %>%
                        mutate(p.adj = case_when(
                        p.adj <0.001 ~ "<0.001"
                        )) %>%
                        mutate(across(c(4:6), round, 2))



rmarkdown::paged_table(post_hoc)

7.1 Post-hoc Test

Examination of standardised residuals indicated that gold members were significantly more likely to be satisfied (adjusted residual = 17.6) than expected, while Bronze (adjusted residual = -9.5) and Silver (adjusted residual = -8.1) members were significantly underrepresented in the satisfied category. Similarly, Bronze (adjusted residual = 4.7) and Silver (adjusted residual = 4.6) members were over represented among unsatisfied customers, while Gold members were absent from this category (-9.3).

8 Effect of Discounts on Purchase Behaviour

The descriptive statistics for the independent samples t-test were obtained by calculating the mean and standard deviation of the variable total spend for discount applied and then rounded off to two decimals. Using the mutate function from the dplyr package, the column “Variance” was created. Furthermore, the case_when function was used to compute the individual variances for discount applied by taking the square root of the standard deviation. At a glace, we can observe that the variances are roughly equal.

8.1 Group Statistics

t_test_descriptive <- df %>%
                            group_by(discount_applied) %>%
                            summarise(n = n(),
                                      Mean = round(mean(total_spend_transformed), 2),
                                      Standard_Deviation =
                                        round(sd(total_spend_transformed), 2))



t_test_descriptive <- t_test_descriptive %>%
                                      mutate(Variance = case_when(
                                      Standard_Deviation == 461.18 ~ round(sqrt(461.18), 2),
                                      Standard_Deviation == 213.59 ~ round(sqrt(213.59), 2)
                                      ))


rmarkdown::paged_table(t_test_descriptive)

8.2 T-Test Model

A two-tailed independent samples t-test was conducted using the “rstatix” library package to compare the total spending between customers who had a discount applied and those who did not. There was no significant difference in total spending for customers with a discount (M = 819.84 , SD = 213.59) and without a discount (M = 870.74, SD = 461.18 ), t(348) = 1.32, p = 0.19 The effect size, as measured by Cohen’s d, was d = 0.14, indicating a small effect size.

library(rstatix)
t_test_model <- t_test(data = df, 
                       total_spend_transformed ~ discount_applied, 
                       var.equal = TRUE,
                       detailed = TRUE, 
                       conf.level = 0.95) %>%
                mutate_if(is.numeric, ~round(.,2))


rmarkdown::paged_table(t_test_model)
t_test_effect <- cohens_d(data = df, 
                          total_spend_transformed ~ discount_applied,
                          var.equal = TRUE) %>%
                mutate_if(is.numeric, ~round(.,2))



rmarkdown::paged_table(t_test_effect)
